definition.value: A 1,2-thazole that is 4-isothiazolin-3-one bearing a methyl group on the nitrogen atom. It is a powerful biocide and preservative and is the minor active ingredient in the commercial product Kathon(TM).

A 1,2-thiazole that is 4-isothiazolin-3-one bearing a methyl group on the nitrogen atom and a chlorine at C-5. It is a powerful biocide and preservative and is the major active ingredient in the commercial product Kathon(TM).
An inorganic salt of sodium, the anion of which is the aurothiosulfate(3-) linear coordination complex.
An inorganic anion that is a linear coordination complex of gold(I) bound to two thiosulfate ligands.
A macromolecule composed of repeating gamma-benzyl-L-glutamyl units.
A macromolecule composed of repeating 1-methyl-1-{[(1',3',3'-trimethyl-1',3'-dihydrospiro[chromene-2,2'-indol]-6-yl)oxy]carbonyl}ethylene units.
A hydrochloride that is the dihydrochloride of ethylenediamine.
A major heartwood norlignan characterised by a core trans-3-p-hydroxyphenyl-1-phenylpropene structural unit.
An alpha-D-glucoside deoxygenated at C-2 and C-6.
Any member of the group of plant secondary metabolites with a diphenylpentane skeleton.
A macromolecule composed of repeating substituted or un-substituted phenyleneoxy units.
A macromolecule composed of repeating 1,4-oxyphenylene units.
A macromolecule composed of repeating 2,6-dimethyl-1,4-phenyleneoxy units.
The hydrochloride salt of L-lysine
A tetracyclic antibacterial agent derived from neomycin, being a glycoside ester of neamine and neobiosamine C.
An aminoglycoside sulfate salt that is the sulfate salt of neamine; a component of neomycin sulfate.
The aminoglycoside sulfate salt that is the sulfate salt of neomycin B; a component of neomycin sulfate.
The aminoglycoside sulfate salt that is the sulfate salt of neomycin C; a component of neomycin sulfate.
A kaurane diterpenoid compound having a 16alpha-hydroxy substituent.
A norlignan that is a derivative of agatharesinol in which  the aromatic ring B has an additional hydroxy substituent ortho to the one present in the parent compound.
A norlignan that is an isomer of agatharesinol in which the dihydroxypentene side chain is cyclised.
A norlignan that is a derivative of sugiresinol in which the aromatic ring B has an additional hydroxy substituent.
A dehydroamino acid derived from glycine.

A monohydroxybenzoic acid consisting of 2-hydroxybenzoic acid having nitro substituents at the 3- and 5-positions. It is used in colorimetric testing for the presence of free carbonyl groups (C=O) in reducing sugars.
An N-substituted diamine that consists of 1,6-hexanediamine bearing a 2,4-dinitro-6-carboxyphenyl substituent.
A glycerol ether in which guaiacyl and guaiacylglycerol subunits are joined by an arylglycerol-beta-aryl (beta-O-4) linkage.
A galactobiose comprising an alpha-D-galactopyranose residue and a D-galactopyranose residue joined via an alpha-(1->3) linkage.
A cephalosporin carboxylate anion having (R)-mandelamido and N-methylthiotetrazole side-groups.
A primary amine comprising an octane skeleton with amino substituents at carbon positions 1 and 8; and an aminomethyl substituent at position 5.
A cephalosporin compound having (R)-O-formylmandelamido and N-methylthiotetrazole side groups. It is used (as the sodium salt) as a progrug for cefamandole.

A cephalosporin carboxylic acid anion having methoxy, 2-thienylacetamido and carbamoyloxymethyl side-groups, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of the semisynthetic cephamycin antibiotic cefoxitin.
An acrylic macromolecule prepared from acrylamide or a derivative of acrylamide.
A cephalosporin carboxylic acid anion having [(5-methyl-1,3,4-thiadiazol-2-yl)sulfanyl]methyl and (1H-tetrazol-1-ylacetyl)amino side-groups, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of cefazolin.

A cephalosporin carboxylis acid anion having 2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetylamino and [(2-methyl-5,6-dioxo-1,2,5,6-tetrahydro-1,2,4-triazin-3-yl)sulfanyl]methyl side-groups, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of ceftriaxone.
An EC 1.4.3.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-NH2 group, oxygen as acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of diamine oxidase (EC 1.4.3.22).
Phenylhydrazine substituted at the para position by a chloro group.
An amphipathic bisbiguanide with a structure consisting of two (2-ethylhexyl)guanide units linked by a hexamethylene bridge.
A class of oral hypoglycemic drugs used for diabetes mellitus or prediabetes treatment. They have a structure based on the 2-carbamimidoylguanidine skeleton.
A compound made up of a guaiacyl core with an alpha-glyceryl substituent para to the aromatic hydroxy group.
The carboxylate anion of 1,2-didehydroglycine.
Any organic heterotricyclic compound based on a skeleton comprised of an oxazine ring fused onto a quinoline system.
A diterpenoid compound having a kaurane skeleton.
The hydrate that is the monohydrate of the cephalosporin cefadroxil.
A  bromoamino acid comprising an L-tyrosine core with a bromo- substituent ortho to the hydroxy group on the benzene ring.
A cephalosporin carboxylic acid anion having a 7beta-[(2R)-2-amino-2-(4-hydroxyphenyl)acetyl]amino side-chain, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of the cephalosporin cefadroxil.

A cephalosporin carboxylic acid anion having acetoxymethyl and [2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetyl]amino side-groups, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of the cephalosporin cefotaxime.
